TEXT(beginproblem());
Context("Form");
$var = list_random('x','y','z','t','r','m','n','a','b','c');
Context()->variables->are($var=>'Real');
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

do {
   $a = random(2,5,1);
   $b = random($a+1,8,1);
} until (gcd($a,$b)==1);
$num = list_random(2,3,5,7);

$answer = Formula("root($b,$num*$var^$a)");

#####################################################

BEGIN_PGML

Convert [`[$num]^{\frac{1}{[$b]}} [$var]^{\frac{[$a]}{[$b]}} `] to a radical expression.

[@KeyboardInstructions("To enter [`\\sqrt[n]{x}`], type [|root(n,x)|]*.");@]**

[__]{$answer}{10}

END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

Fraction exponents can be converted into radicals this way:

    [`` x^{\frac{m}{n}} = (x^{m})^{\frac{1}{n}} =  \sqrt[n]{x^{m}} ``]

For this problem, we have:

    [`` [$num]^{\frac{[$c]}{[$b]}} [$var]^{\frac{[$a]}{[$b]}} = ([$num]^{[$c]} [$var]^[$a])^{\frac{1}{[$b]}} = \sqrt[[$b]]{[$num]^{[$c]} [$var]^[$a]} ``]


END_PGML_SOLUTION

